{{LGBT mythology mini}}
[[Greco-Roman mythology]] features [[male homosexuality]] in many of the constituent myths. In addition, there are instances of [[cross-dressing]], and of [[androgyny]] which in post-1990s gender terminology has been grouped{{whom|date=April 2015}} under the acronym [[LGBT]].
==Overall== These myths have been described as being crucially influential on Western [[LGBT literature]], with the original myths being constantly re-published and re-written, and the relationships and characters serving as icons.<ref name="Pequigney1">{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/literature/classical_myth.html|title=Classical Mythology|page=1|date=2002|publisher=[[glbtq.com]]|accessdate=February 5, 2015|last=Pequigney|first=Joseph|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415180456/http://www.glbtq.com/literature/classical_myth.html|archivedate=April 15, 2014|df=}}</ref> In comparison, lesbianism is rarely found in classical myths.<ref>Compton, p. 97, "Rome and Greece: Lesbianism"</ref>
==Instances== ===Homosexuality and bisexuality=== Dionysus, a god gestated in the thigh of his father Zeus, after his mother died from being overwhelmed by Zeus's true form, has been dubbed "a patron god of hermaphrodites and transvestites" by Roberto C. Ferrari in the 2002 ''Encyclopedia of Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual, Transgender, and Queer Culture''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.glbtq.com/arts/subjects_dionysus.html |title=Subjects in the Visual Arts: Dionysus |first=Roberto C. |last=Ferrari |publisher=glbtq.com |date=September 19, 2002 |accessdate=April 8, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090712090224/http://www.glbtq.com/arts/subjects_dionysus.html |archivedate=July 12, 2009 |df= }}</ref> Other gods are sometimes considered patrons of homosexual love between males, such as the love goddess [[Aphrodite]] and gods in her retinue, such as the [[Erotes (mythology)|Erotes]]: [[Eros]], [[Himeros]] and [[Pothos (mythology)#Pothos|Pothos]].<ref name=conner64>Conner & Sparks (1998), p. 64, "Aphrodite"</ref><ref>Conner & Sparks (1998), p. 133, "Erotes"</ref> Eros is also part of a trinity of gods that played roles in homoerotic relationships, along with [[Heracles]] and [[Hermes]], who bestowed qualities of Beauty (and Loyalty), strength, and eloquence, respectively, onto male lovers.<ref>Conner & Sparks (1998), p. 132, "Eros"</ref> In the poetry of [[Sappho]], Aphrodite is identified as the patron of lesbians.<ref name=conner64/>
{{div col|colwidth=22em}} *[[Achilles and Patroclus]]<ref name=Pequigney5>Pequigney (2002), p.5</ref> *[[Achilles#Troilus|Achilles and Troilus]]<ref>Penczak (2003), p. 17</ref> *[[Agamemnon]] and [[Argynnus]]<ref>Clement of Alexandria, ''[[Protrepticus (Clement)|Protrepticus]]'' II.38.2</ref> *[[Ameinias (mythology)|Ameinias]] and [[Narcissus (mythology)|Narcissus]]<ref name=Pequigney5/> *[[Branchus|Apollo and Branchus]]<ref>[[Conon (mythographer)|Conon]], 33</ref> *[[Carnus|Apollo and Carnus]]<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], ''Description of Greece'', 3.13.4–5</ref> *[[Cyparissus|Apollo and Cyparissus]]<ref>[[Ovid]]'s ''[[Metamorphoses]]'', 10</ref> *[[Hyacinth (mythology)|Apollo and Hyacinth]]<ref name=Pequigney2>Pequigney (2002), p.2</ref> *[[Hymenaios|Apollo and Hymenaios]]<ref name=Pequigney2/> *[[Apollo]] and [[Iapis]]<ref>[[Virgil]], ''[[Aeneid]]'', 391-394</ref> *[[Chrysippus (mythology)|Chrysippus and Laius]]<ref name=Pequigney4/> *[[Cycnus (king of Liguria)|Cycnus and Phaethon]]<ref>[[Ovid]], ''[[Metamorphoses]]'', 2, 367 sqq.</ref> *[[Daphnis|Daphnis and Pan]]<ref name=Pequigney3>Pequigney (2002), p.3</ref> *[[Dionysus]] and [[Ampelos|Ampelus]]<ref name=Pequigney3/> *[[Dionysus]] and [[Prosymnus]]<ref>The seduction of the Mediterranean: writing, art, and homosexual fantasy - Page 231 by Robert Aldrich</ref> *[[Nisus and Euryalus|Euryalus and Nisus]]<ref>Madness unchained By Lee Fratantuono; p.139</ref> *[[Eurybarus]] and [[Alcyoneus (Son of Diomos)|Alcyoneus]]<ref>[[Antoninus Liberalis]], ''Metamorphoses'', 8</ref> *[[Abderus|Heracles and Abderus]] *[[Hylas|Heracles and Hylas]]<ref name=Pequigney3/> *[[Iolaus|Heracles and Iolaus]]<ref name=Pequigney4>Pequigney (2002), p.4</ref> *[[Crocus (mythology)|Hermes and Crocus]]<ref>[[Ovid]]'s ''[[Metamorphoses]]'', 4</ref> *[[Hermes]] and [[Perseus]]<ref>Pseudo-Hyginus, ''[[De Astronomica]]'' 2.12.</ref> *[[Iphis (Cretan)|Ianthe and Iphis]]<ref>Classical mythology By Helen Morales; p.93</ref> *[[Poseidon]] and [[Nerites (mythology)|Nerites]]<ref>[[Claudius Aelianus|Aelian]], ''On Animals'', 14. 28</ref> *[[Pelops#Tantalus' savage banquet|Poseidon and Pelops]]<ref name=Pequigney2/> *[[Polyeidos]] and [[Glaucus (son of Minos)|Glaucus]]<ref>Sotades By Herbert Hoffmann, p.16</ref> *[[Orpheus#Death|Orpheus and the Thracians]]<ref name=Pequigney4/> *[[Orpheus]] and [[Kalais]]<ref name=Pequigney4/> *[[Silvanus (mythology)|Silvanus]] and [[Cyparissus#The commentaries of Servius|Cyparissus]]<ref>The Vatican Mythographers By Ronald E. Pepin; p.17</ref> *[[Thamyris]] and [[Hyacinth (mythology)|Hyacinth]]<ref name=Pseudo-Apollodorus>[[Pseudo-Apollodorus]], 1. 3.3.</ref> *[[Anemoi#Zephyrus|Zephyrus]] and [[Hyacinth (mythology)|Hyacinth]]<ref name=Pseudo-Apollodorus/> *[[Callisto (mythology)#Myth|Zeus (Artemis) and Callisto]]<ref>Downing, p.198</ref> *[[Ganymede (mythology)|Zeus and Ganymede]]<ref name=Pequigney1/> {{colend}}
===Transgender and transsexual=== The sex-change theme also occurred in classical mythology. The reason for the transformation varies, as in the case of Sypretes (Συπρετεσ) or [[Siproites]] (Σιπροιτεσ), a hunter from [[Crete]], who was transformed to a woman by [[Artemis]] after having seen the goddess bathing.<ref>[[Antoninus Liberalis]], cited by Francis Celoria. ''The Metamorphoses of Antoninus Liberalis: A Translation with Commentary'', [https://books.google.com.vn/books?id=9_Eolzuv0eQC&pg=PA71&lpg=PA71&dq=siproites pp.71].</ref><ref>''Orion: The Myth of the Hunter and the Huntress'', [https://books.google.com.vn/books?id=tD4lJxC95mEC&pg=PA125&dq=Siproites pp.125-126]. University of California Press.</ref>
There was also a motif of a woman needing to disguise herself as a male and later being transformed into a biological male by mysterious forces (mainly the [[Greek gods|gods]]). In the cases of [[Iphis (Cretan)|Iphis]] and [[Leucippus (daughter of Galatea)|Leucippus]], the woman's mother was pressured (by her husband) to bear a male child so the protagonist was forced to impersonate a male from birth. Later in life, manhood was granted through the blessing of a deity ([[Juno (mythology)|Juno]]/[[Hera]] in Iphis' case and [[Leto]] in Leucippus').
[[Caeneus]] and [[Mestra]], each of who was a mate of a god (Caeneus was a rape victim of [[Poseidon]]/[[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]] and Mestra was a lover of [[Apollo]]), were granted manhood by the said god. Mestra, however, had the ability to [[shapeshifting|change her shape voluntarily]], instead of staying in male form like Caeneus and other instances above.
[[Tiresias]], on the other hand, became female because he struck a couple of copulating snakes, displeasing [[Hera]], who punished him by transforming Tiresias into a woman. Later the sentence was remitted, due to either trampling on the mating snakes or avoiding them, and she became male again. In another version, Tiresias' sex-change was caused by an argument between [[Zeus]] and Hera, on which they debated whether a male or a female had greater pleasure in [[sex]], so they transformed him to a female to experiment.
*[[Caeneus]] *[[Iphis (Cretan)|Iphis]] *[[Leucippus (daughter of Galatea)|Leucippus]] *[[Mestra]] *Siproites *[[Tiresias]]
===Androgynes and intersex=== [[Aphroditus]] was an androgynous Aphrodite from Cyprus, in later mythology became known as [[Hermaphroditus]] (also the namesake of the word ''[[hermaphrodite]]'') the son of Hermes and Aphrodite.
*[[Agdistis]] ([[Cybele]]) *[[Aphroditus]] *The [[Enaree]]s *[[Hermaphroditus]] *The [[Machlyes]] *[[Phanes (mythology)|Phanes]] *[[Salmacis]] *The [[Scythians]] *[[Venus Barbata]] *[[Venus Castina]]
